			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: For the Sys Admins and Tech Ops folks...
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1789167">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Quick answer to this one:<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				What would I, as a member of the development team, have to convince you to let us touch production more regularly?
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>If this is a public company subject to Sarbanes-Oxley audits and the production system affects financial reporting: it may be neigh-impossible short of getting laws changed.  If SOX compliance is a big deal for your company the separation of duties policies may be there explicitly to clarify chains of accountability-- often explicitly preventing software developers from having any write-access at all to production systems.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Ikeya</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1788452#post1788452" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">...How can I convince you let me deploy to production servers more regularly?  Team is facing an issue where we're only allowed to deploy at most once every 3 months.  This tends to be a time consuming and tedious process that takes up most of the night and the following morning.  We'd like to be able to knock the time between deployments down (ideally moving towards a Continuous Deployment or Delivery model, but that's a way off).</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Generally speaking, operations first priority is keeping the engines running.  If you have a web application that generates revenue for the company, downtime translates pretty directly into lost revenue.  From an ops perspective, release cycles and change controls are in place to reduce costly downtime (or the risk of it).  They're also in place to help ensure accountability rests with people of the right pay grade and that institutional ops knowledge is preserved as much as possible.<br />
<br />
Why is the deployment process so long and tedious?  Where is the bottleneck?  Where is there bloat?  How much downtime is required for a particular change?  <br />
<br />
Are there other cost reasons why it is the way it is?  What's preventing an A/B deployment model or something similar?  <br />
<br />
How stable does the application tend to be after a release?  How often have developers introduced bugs that cause webservers to crash nightly at 2:00 AM, requiring the admins to wake up and restart the services?  If devs have a reputation for forgetting to turn off debug flags or allowing other crap into production then there may be a lot of extra QA and review processes required to certify the code into production.  Because in some cases, even when it was bad code that caused the site to go down and impact revenue, the downtime still counts against Operations uptime SLAs.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
		<div class="postfoot">
