		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: For the Sys Admins and Tech Ops folks...
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1789242">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Merkus</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1788670#post1788670" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Seriously. You need to research, build your arguments and make this pitch to someone in management. They are the people who can make this customer focused decision. This is not a decision that should be in the hands of a system admin to start with.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I agree except for the absolutely toxic attitude of circumventing the sysadmin and categorizing them as people who just get in the way and get grumpy about having to answer service calls.<br />
<br />
Operations care about the customer too, they just care about different things.  They measure in nines of uptime rather than whether the cool new feature makes it in before an arbitrary business deadline.  Production downtime is kind of like a forest fire except with piles of money instead of trees.<br />
<br />
Do you guys remember how fucking awesome Everquest was by 2000 or so?  When WoW came out, people basically accepted weekly downtime as a matter of course.  With EQ, people could stay logged in for MONTHS at a time.  That's a huge tell that there was a solid relationship between developers and system administrators.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
